03925nam a22005175i 9780226707174DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20102010ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a9780226707174  a(DE-B1597)525078  a(OCoLC)688291765  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 4aQB525b.G22 2010eb 7aSCI0000002bisacsh04a523.7/4222  aUB 2481qSEPA2rvk0(DE-625)rvk/145327:1 aGalilei, Galileo, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aOn Sunspots /cGalileo Galilei, Christoph Scheiner. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2010] 4c©2010  a1 online resource (432 p.) :b108 halftones, 2 line drawings  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of abbreviations -- tPreface -- t1. Introduction -- t2. Sunspots before the telescope -- t3. Turning the telescope to the Sun: Thomas Harriot and Johannes and David Fabricius -- t4. Christoph Scheiner -- t5. Tres Epistolae -- t6. Galileo answers Apelles -- t7. Galileo’s first letter -- t8. Galileo’s second letter -- t9. A more accurate inquiry from Ingolstadt -- t10. Accuratior Disquisitio -- t11. Galileo responds and goes into print -- t12. Galileo’s third letter -- t13. Rematch, 1630–1632 -- tAppendixes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aGalileo’s telescopic discoveries, and especially his observation of sunspots, caused great debate in an age when the heavens were thought to be perfect and unchanging. Christoph Scheiner, a Jesuit mathematician, argued that sunspots were planets or moons crossing in front of the Sun. Galileo, on the other hand, countered that the spots were on or near the surface of the Sun itself, and he supported his position with a series of meticulous observations and mathematical demonstrations that eventually convinced even his rival. On Sunspots collects the correspondence that constituted the public debate, including the first English translation of Scheiner’s two tracts as well as Galileo’s three letters, which have previously appeared only in abridged form. In addition, Albert Van Helden and Eileen Reeves have supplemented the correspondence with lengthy introductions, extensive notes, and a bibliography. The result will become the standard work on the subject, essential for students and historians of astronomy, the telescope, and early modern Catholicism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aSunspotsvEarly works to 1800. 7aSCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  agalileo, sunspots, telescope, discovery, astronomy, cosmology, science, observation, christoph scheiner, scientific debate, religion, catholicism, moon, planets, sun, heliocentric, unchanging universe, nonfiction, copernican revolution, english translation, history, philosophy, mathematics, heavens, theology, doctrine, celestial, jupiter, satellites, thomas harriot.1 aHelden, Albert van.1 aReeves, Eileen.1 aScheiner, Christoph, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226707174423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226707174/original  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles